[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "If thou see the ass of him that hateth thee . . . —",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The sense is clear, but the words are greatly disputed. If a man sees his enemy’s ass prostrate under its burthen, he is to help to raise it up. In this case he owes a double duty—(1) to his enemy, and (2) to the suffering animal. Geddes’ emendation of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "’azar ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for ’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "azab, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "in all the three places where the verb occurs, is the simplest and best of those suggested. The passage would then run: “If thou see the ass of him that hateth thee lying under his burthen, and wouldest forbear to help it, thou shalt surely help with him”—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "the owner.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
